\description{
A SpaDES "experiment" is a way of running a single "global" script,
but with varying \code{inputs}, \code{parameters}, \code{paths} etc. This allows users to
run, for example, replication of stochastic models, hypothesis testing with
different data inputs, scenarios of different human decisions, build
large datasets of alternative mechanisms to enable ensemble modeling,
and other possibilities.
}
\details{
The structure of an experiment is a \code{data.frame} (or \code{data.table}) where
each row describes one set of values to be assigned to variables in
the \code{.GlobalEnv}. When an experiment is run using one of the \code{experimentXXX}
family of functions,
e.g., \code{experimentFuture}, \code{experimentTmux}, \code{experimentSBATCH}, this
data.frame is translated into a \code{queue} data.frame that has all the
same columns and rows as the experiment, plus a few more, including \code{status},
\code{claimed_by} etc. to help run the experiment.
After creating the queue, the function will spawn a number of
independent R "worker" sessions (according to \code{n_workers} or \code{cores}).
Each of these workers will select a single row, assign the values
in each user-specified column to an object in the
\code{.GlobalEnv} whose name is the column name.
For example, if the \code{data.frame} has 2 rows and a column named
\code{runName} where the row values are \verb{"trial1"`` and }"trial2"\verb{, then during the }experimentXXX\verb{function call, the first R script will run:}runName <- "trial1"; source(global_path)\verb{, and the second R script will run: }runName <- "trial2"; source(global_path)\verb{.  The "status" column will have initial values of "PENDING" for all rows.  The workers will take the next row in the  queue that is "PENDING" (or "INTERRUPTED"),  skipping any rows that have "DONE" or any other value. When a worker is done, without error, the }status` column will be marked as
DONE in that row in a shared queue, and moves on to the next PENDING row.

Currently, there are 3 different ways of running an \code{experiment}. All
share the queue and the run naming convention; however,
they differ only in \emph{how} parallel workers are spawned.

\describe{
\item{\code{\link[=experimentTmux]{experimentTmux()}}}{Allows the most interactivity and so
is helpful when there is still debugging to perform. This will
only work on a computer that has \code{tmux} installed. The function
spawns one tmux pane per worker, optionally across
ssh-reachable machines. Best for interactive use where you want to
watch workers live (\verb{tmux attach}). Workers can be stopped with
\code{\link[=tmuxKillPanes]{tmuxKillPanes()}}.}
\item{\code{\link[=experimentFuture]{experimentFuture()}}}{When there is little to no debugging
necessary, this function will use background R processes using
either \code{callr::r_bg()} if all workers are local,
or \code{future::cluster} if some of the workers are on different machines.
Best for stable scripts. Workers can be stopped with \code{\link[=killExperimentFuture]{killExperimentFuture()}}.}
\item{\code{\link[=experimentSBATCH]{experimentSBATCH()}}}{One Slurm batch job per worker. Best for
HPC clusters with \code{sbatch} / \code{squeue} / \code{scancel}. Block with
\code{\link[=awaitExperimentSBATCH]{awaitExperimentSBATCH()}} (polls \code{squeue}) or stop with
\code{\link[=killExperimentSBATCH]{killExperimentSBATCH()}} (graceful via stop files; \code{force = TRUE}
issues \code{scancel}). Inspect generated job scripts with
\code{dry_run = TRUE}.}
}

All experimentXXX functions accept the same core arguments:

\describe{
\item{\code{df}}{The parameter grid; one row = one job. Column names become
R variables in the worker's \code{.GlobalEnv} before \code{global.R} is sourced.}
\item{\code{global_path}}{Path to the R script each worker sources per job.
Must be on a filesystem visible to all workers (matters for
\code{experimentSBATCH()} and remote-host modes of the other two).}
\item{\code{queue_path}}{Path to the local RDS queue file. Workers
coordinate through file-based locks on this file; remove it (or
point a fresh path) to start over, leave it to resume.}
\item{\code{runNameLabel}}{Quoted expression evaluated against each row to
derive a human-readable identifier (used in log messages, sentinel
filenames, and \code{tmuxListPanes()} output). Default is the first two
non-meta columns of the queue.}
\item{\code{statusCalculate}}{Optional quoted expression that inspects the
job's outputs and returns up-to-date status / heartbeat metadata.
\link{statusCalculate_LandR} and \link{statusCalculate_FireSenseFit} are
pre-built blocks for the most common SpaDES module outputs.}
\item{\code{ss_id}}{Optional Google Sheets / Drive folder ID. When provided,
workers mirror queue state to a sheet so a remote stakeholder can
watch progress in a browser. With \code{ss_id = NULL} (default) the
queue is purely local -- no Google APIs are touched.}
}

A typical usage pattern:

\preformatted{
df <- expand.grid(.scenario = c("A", "B"), .rep = 1:2,
                  stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
ef <- experimentFuture(df = df, global_path = "global.R",
                       n_workers = 2L, log_dir = "logs")
awaitExperimentFuture(ef)         # block until all rows DONE
}

Swap \code{experimentFuture()} for \code{experimentTmux()} or \code{experimentSBATCH()}
(adjusting \code{cores} / \code{n_workers} / \code{sbatch_opts}) and the rest of the
driver script is unchanged.
}
\section{Why not just run \verb{Rscript -e ...} per row?}{


At the kernel, that is exactly what each runner does. A worker assigns the
row's columns into \code{.GlobalEnv} and calls \code{source("global.R")}, which is
equivalent to:

\preformatted{
Rscript -e '.ELFind <- "6.3.1"; .rep <- 1; source("global.R")'
Rscript -e '.ELFind <- "6.3.1"; .rep <- 2; source("global.R")'
}

That works for a handful of rows you launch by hand. As you add scenarios,
machines, restarts, or stakeholders, the bookkeeping grows past what's
comfortable to maintain by hand. The runner functions are just that
bookkeeping.

Concretely, a hand-rolled \verb{Rscript -e ...} per row gives you no answer for:

\describe{
\item{Concurrency control}{Two shells launched at the same second can
both pick the same row. The experimentXXX functions take an exclusive \code{filelock} lock
on the queue between read and write, so each row is claimed at most
once across all workers and machines.}
\item{Resume after crash / ctrl-C}{If a worker dies mid-job, the row is
stuck "in progress" with no record. The experimentXXX functions mark the row RUNNING
when claimed and DONE / INTERRUPTED when finished, so the next launch
skips DONE rows and (optionally, via \code{\link[=tmuxRefreshQueueStatus]{tmuxRefreshQueueStatus()}} or
\code{\link[=experimentFutureList]{experimentFutureList()}} \code{(kill = TRUE)}) demotes orphaned RUNNING
rows back to PENDING for re-claim.}
\item{Worker-pool sizing}{\verb{Rscript &; Rscript &; Rscript &} scales as
"one process per row", which thrashes the box once you exceed the
core count. The experimentXXX functions take \code{n_workers} and let each worker pull
rows in sequence, so you cap parallelism explicitly.}
\item{Cross-machine claims}{Spawning N rows on each of M machines means
either replicating the parameter grid by hand (and risking duplicate
work) or sharding it (and losing dynamic load-balancing). With the
experimentXXX functions, every worker on every machine pulls from the same queue, so
a slow machine just claims fewer rows.}
\item{Live observability}{\code{Rscript -e} writes nothing structured -- you
scrape PIDs and tail logs. The experimentXXX functions maintain a queue with
\code{status} / \code{claimed_by} / \code{started_at} / \code{process_id} / \code{machine_name}
so \code{\link[=queueRead]{queueRead()}} gives a full snapshot, and \code{\link[=experimentFutureList]{experimentFutureList()}}
can enumerate live workers (and kill them) cluster-wide.}
\item{Remote-stakeholder visibility}{When \code{ss_id} is supplied, the
queue is mirrored to a Google Sheet a collaborator can open in a
browser; without that, "how is the run going?" requires SSH
access to the runner machine.}
\item{Outputs accounting}{\code{\link[=queueUploadMissing]{queueUploadMissing()}} / \code{\link[=outScenarios]{outScenarios()}}
anti-join the queue against the Drive upload folder so you can see
which DONE rows still need to be packaged and uploaded.}
\item{Run-name + status hooks}{\code{runNameLabel} and \code{statusCalculate}
give one place to derive directory names and inspect output
artifacts -- both per-runner and in \code{\link[=tmuxRefreshQueueStatus]{tmuxRefreshQueueStatus()}} for
post-hoc rescans -- without each \code{global.R} re-implementing them.}
}

If you only ever run two rows on one machine and never restart, the
two-line shell version is fine. The experimentXXX functions exist for the cases past
that.
}

\section{Cross-machine propagation (cluster modes)}{


When you launch on more than one machine -- \code{experimentTmux(cores =
c("mega", "birds"))} or \code{experimentFuture(cores = c("localhost",
"camas"))} -- \code{.setup_remote_machine()} runs once per unique
remote host before any worker starts. It tries to make the remote R
session look enough like the local one that \code{global.R} runs the
same way. What it propagates / sets up:

\describe{
\item{Package versions}{
\code{SpaDES.project} itself is rsynced from the local
\code{.libPaths()[1]} to the remote (or, if loaded via
\code{devtools::load_all()}, the source tree is rsynced and
\code{R CMD INSTALL}-ed). \code{Require} is version- and
\code{RemoteSha}-checked and rsynced if it's older or comes from a
different source than locally. Then \code{Require::Install()}
installs every package in \code{SpaDES.project}'s \code{Imports} /
\code{Depends} / \code{LinkingTo}, plus any \code{Suggests}
installed locally (so optional runtime dependencies like
\code{googlesheets4}, \code{cli}, etc. follow along but the dev
toolchain doesn't).
}
\item{Compiled-from-source packages}{
\code{terra}, \code{sf}, \code{rgdal}, \code{rgeos}, \code{lwgeom}
are forced to compile from source on the remote (so they link
against the remote's \code{libgdal.so} etc., which may be a
different soversion than localhost's).
}
\item{System libraries}{
A best-effort \code{sudo -n apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends}
of the dev headers needed for the source-compiled packages
(\code{libgdal-dev}, \code{libssl-dev}, \code{libcurl4-openssl-dev},
\code{libxml2-dev}, fonts/graphics, ...). Runs non-interactively;
if passwordless sudo isn't configured the failure is logged and
setup continues, expecting the libraries to be there already.
}
\item{R startup environment}{
The remote \code{~/.Rprofile} gets refreshed with
\code{.libPaths(c(<local_lib>, .libPaths()))},
\code{options(repos = c("https://predictiveecology.r-universe.dev",
    <local repos>))}, \code{options(defaultPackages = ...)} (so the
remote uses the same minimal default-attached set as a fresh
\code{Rscript}), and \code{Sys.setenv(CURL_CA_BUNDLE, SSL_CERT_FILE)}
pointing at the system CA bundle (so \code{libcurl} can do HTTPS
even when \code{/etc/profile.d/} isn't sourced under non-login
SSH). The remote \code{$BASH_ENV}, if set, is wrapped in a
subshell guard so a misbehaving \code{sleep $UNSET} can't kill
the SSH command shell before R starts.
}
\item{GitHub credentials}{
The local \code{GITHUB_PAT} (read from \code{gitcreds::gitcreds_get()}
or a caller-supplied \code{local_pat_file}) is written to the
remote \code{~/.Renviron} (chmod 0600) and to a per-lib file
\code{<local_lib>/.spades_github_pat} that's read at the top of
\code{~/.Rprofile}. \code{git credential approve} is also called
so command-line \code{git} on the remote authenticates the same
way. Required for \code{pak} to install private modules / dev
packages from GitHub.
}
\item{Google credentials}{
The experimentXXX functions pass \code{email} + \code{cache_path} into each
worker; the worker calls
\code{googlesheets4::gs4_auth(email = email, cache = cache_path)}
non-interactively against the same cached OAuth token directory
the local session uses. The token directory itself isn't pushed
(it's expected to already exist via NFS or a prior login on the
remote); only the \code{gargle_oauth_email} /
\code{gargle_oauth_cache} options are forwarded so the same
identity is selected. If the cache isn't there, the worker prints
a \code{gs4_auth warning} and continues without GS access.
}
\item{User code: \code{R/} folder + modules}{
The directory next to \code{global.R} called \code{R/} (where
project-specific helper functions live) is \code{rsync -a --delete}-ed
to the remote, so anything \code{global.R} \code{source()}s from
\code{R/} works there too. With \code{copyModules = TRUE} the
SpaDES module path (\code{getOption("spades.modulePath")}) is
also rsynced, so module code stays in step.
}
\item{The job artifacts themselves}{
\code{global.R} and the queue \code{.rds} are scp'd into the
same path on the remote (or, if the path is already on NFS such
as \code{/mnt/shared_cache/...}, they're effectively no-ops --
same absolute path on both ends).
}
}

Net effect: \code{global.R} on \code{camas} sees the same packages at
the same versions, the same \code{GITHUB_PAT}, the same \code{R/}
helpers, the same SSL trust store, and the same Google identity as
\code{global.R} on \code{mega}. Hand-rolling all of that for each
remote machine before each run is the bulk of what makes
"\code{Rscript -e ...} on N hosts" miserable in practice; the experimentXXX functions
do it once per unique host per call.
}

\section{Managing remote workers from the calling machine}{


Once \code{experimentFuture(cores = c("localhost", "camas", "dougfir"))}
is launched, the workers on \code{camas} and \code{dougfir} are no
longer reachable via local \code{ps} / \code{tools::pskill()} -- they
are R processes on other machines.  \code{\link{experimentFutureList}()}
is the cluster-wide handle for them.  Pass it the \code{ef} object
and it will:

\enumerate{
\item Read the queue file (which is the authoritative record:
every claim writes \code{machine_name} + \code{process_id} under
a \code{filelock}, so workers on every machine appear there even
when they didn't redirect their stdout to a discoverable
\verb{worker_NN.log}).
\item Probe each entry in \code{ef$cores} once with
\code{ssh <core> hostname -s} to build a map from OS hostname
(which is what \code{Sys.info()[["nodename"]]} writes to the
queue) to the SSH alias the master used to reach it
(e.g. \code{A159604 -> dougfir}).  This is needed because
\code{ssh A159604} typically fails -- only \code{ssh dougfir}
resolves via \code{~/.ssh/config} / \code{/etc/hosts}.
\item For every \code{status == "RUNNING"} row, verify the worker
is actually alive: \code{file.exists("/proc/<pid>")} for the
local machine, batched \code{ssh <alias> "[ -d /proc/<pid> ]"}
for each remote machine (one SSH connection per machine).
\item Return a \code{data.frame} with \code{pid}, \code{machine},
\code{started_at}, \code{queue_path}, \code{runName} for every
live worker -- local and remote, in one table.
}

\code{kill = TRUE} uses the same map to send the chosen signal
(\code{TERM} default, \code{INT} or \code{KILL} on request):
\code{tools::pskill()} for local PIDs and a single batched
\code{ssh <alias> "kill -<sig> p1 p2 ..."} per remote machine.
After signalling, it polls (locally via \code{/proc}, remotely via
SSH) for up to 10 s until the workers actually exit, then runs
\code{\link[=tmuxRefreshQueueStatus]{tmuxRefreshQueueStatus()}} on each unique queue file to demote the
now-orphaned \verb{RUNNING} rows back to \verb{PENDING}.  When
\code{ss_id} was supplied to the original \code{experimentFuture()}
call, an \code{<queue_path>.ss_id} sidecar is left behind;
\code{kill = TRUE} reads it and pushes the same demotion to the
Google Sheet via \code{.gs_demote_after_kill()}, so the GS view
converges with the local queue without a separate cleanup step.

Three usage shapes:

\preformatted{
experimentFutureList(ef)                   # list everything live
experimentFutureList(ef, kill = TRUE)      # graceful TERM + queue refresh
experimentFutureList(ef, kill = TRUE, signal = "KILL")  # immediate
}

Across R sessions, when \code{ef} is gone, drive discovery off the
queue path directly:

\preformatted{
experimentFutureList(queue_paths = "/mnt/shared_cache/.../future_queue.rds")
}

Without \code{ef}, the hostname-to-alias probe is skipped, so the
SSH check uses \code{machine_name} verbatim -- which only works if
the OS hostname is itself reachable via SSH on the calling node
(i.e. it appears in \code{~/.ssh/config} or \code{/etc/hosts} as a
Host entry).  If not, you'll need to either keep \code{ef} in scope
or add the OS hostnames to your SSH config.

Concretely, the things you can do post-launch from the calling
machine without ever opening a terminal on \code{camas} /
\code{dougfir}:

\itemize{
\item See which row each remote worker is currently on.
\item Confirm that a remote worker actually died after a crash /
network blip (otherwise the queue would stay stuck at
\verb{RUNNING} and no one would re-claim).
\item Send \code{SIGTERM} cluster-wide to abort an experiment
mid-run, then immediately re-launch a fixed \code{global.R}
against the same queue (any DONE rows are skipped, demoted
RUNNING rows are re-claimed).
\item Mirror that demotion to the Google Sheet so a stakeholder
watching in a browser sees the change without needing to be
told.
}
}

\section{Resource monitoring (CPU + RAM)}{


\code{\link[=experimentMonitor]{experimentMonitor()}} is the read-only entry point.  Discovery
depends on what you pass:

\itemize{
\item \code{experimentMonitor()} (no args) -- enumerates every
tmux pane on the calling machine across all tmux servers, same
as the historical \code{\link[=tmuxListPanes]{tmuxListPanes()}}.
\item \code{experimentMonitor(ef)} -- queue-driven discovery
across all machines in \code{ef$cores} (with the
hostname-to-SSH-alias probe described above).
\item \code{experimentMonitor(queue_paths = "...")} -- same as
\code{ef} mode, but for cross-session use when the \code{ef}
handle is gone.
}

\code{stats = TRUE} batches \code{ps -o pid=,\%cpu=,rss=,state=}
(locally and via one SSH connection per remote node) to append:

\itemize{
\item \code{state} -- \code{R} (running on CPU), \code{S}
(sleeping / waiting), \code{D} (uninterruptible sleep, often disk
I/O -- persistent \code{D} = hang), \code{T} (stopped),
\code{Z} (zombie), \code{Closed} (R session exited but tmux pane
still open).
\item \code{cpuAvg} -- percent CPU averaged over the process's
lifetime (note: \emph{not} the instantaneous rate \code{htop}
shows).
\item \verb{RAM (GB)} -- resident memory (RSS), 1 decimal place.
\item \code{availableCores} -- total CPUs on the node, from
\code{nproc}.
\item \verb{total RAM (GB)} -- total RAM on the node, from
\code{/proc/meminfo}.
}

\code{availableCores} and \verb{total RAM (GB)} are constant across
all rows on the same node, so each pane's resource use is visible
relative to its node capacity.  Unreachable nodes get \code{NA} for
all their rows; titles missing a parseable \verb{<node>-<pid>} get
\code{NA} too -- one bad pane / unreachable host doesn't poison the
rest of the table.

Single function, three sources, same \code{stats} columns either
way -- so a stakeholder running \code{experimentMonitor(ef, stats =
TRUE)} on a laptop sees the same per-worker CPU / RAM picture that
\code{experimentMonitor(stats = TRUE)} (legacy tmux mode) gives on
the master node.  \code{\link[=tmuxListPanes]{tmuxListPanes()}} is preserved as a thin alias
that calls \code{experimentMonitor()} with no \code{ef}, so older
code keeps working unchanged.

Related families:

\itemize{
\item \link{scenario_family} -- canonical record for one row of \code{df},
reversibly convertible between field values, an output directory
path, and an upload tarball filename.
\item \code{\link[=queueRead]{queueRead()}} / \code{\link[=queueUploadMissing]{queueUploadMissing()}} / \code{\link[=outList]{outList()}} /
\code{\link[=outScenarios]{outScenarios()}} -- helpers for queues persisted to a Google
Sheet plus a Drive upload folder, including the
queue-vs-uploads anti-join.
\item \code{\link[=experimentMonitor]{experimentMonitor()}} -- read-only worker / pane lister.
With no args, scans tmux panes; with \code{ef} or
\code{queue_paths}, scans the queue file's RUNNING rows and
verifies each PID is alive (local /proc, batched SSH for
remotes).  \code{stats = TRUE} adds per-worker CPU / RSS /
state and per-node \code{nproc} / total RAM via batched
\code{ps}.  \code{\link[=tmuxListPanes]{tmuxListPanes()}} is a thin alias for the no-args
form.
\item \code{\link[=tmuxRefreshQueueStatus]{tmuxRefreshQueueStatus()}} / \code{\link[=tmuxFindDuplicates]{tmuxFindDuplicates()}} /
\code{\link[=tmuxKillPanes]{tmuxKillPanes()}} -- operational tools that work regardless of
which runner produced the queue.
\item \code{\link[=experimentFutureList]{experimentFutureList()}} -- \code{experimentFuture}-side
equivalent of \code{tmuxListPanes()}: discovers live workers
across the cluster (driven off the queue file's RUNNING rows
plus an \code{ssh <core> hostname -s} alias probe), and with
\code{kill = TRUE} sends \code{TERM} / \code{INT} / \code{KILL}
to all of them in one call (local via \code{tools::pskill()},
remote batched per machine via SSH), then refreshes the queue
and demotes the matching Google-Sheet rows when an
\code{<queue_path>.ss_id} sidecar is present.
}
}

